82","Europe":"Europe","England":"England, United Kingdom","Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England":"Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pope","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>pope</i> (derived via Old English from Late Latin <i>papa</i> ‘bishop, pope’, from Greek <i>pappas</i> ‘father’, in origin a nursery word.) In the early Christian Church, the Latin term was at first used as a title of respect for male clergy of every rank, but in the Western Church it gradually came to be restricted to bishops, and then only to the bishop of Rome; in the Eastern Church it continued to be used of all priests (see   Popov  ,   Papas  ). The nickname would have been used for a vain or pompous man, or for someone who had played the part of the pope in a pageant or play. The surname is also present in Ireland and Scotland.","North German: variant of   Poppe  .","German: translation of   Pabst  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Popov","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Russian Nikolay, Oleg, Grigoriy, Anatoly, Andrei, Arkadi, Dmitriy, Mikhail, Sergey.  Bulgarian or Macedonian Atanas, Dimitar, Yordan.  Serbian Bosko, Bozidar, Branko.","Russian, Bulgarian, Macedonian, Serbian, and Rusyn: patronymic from <i>pop</i> ‘priest’, from Greek <i>pappas</i> ‘father’ (compare English   Pope  ). The name may sometimes derive from a nickname, but celibacy was not enjoined on priests of the Orthodox Church and so the name can indeed mean ‘son of the priest’. In many cases, however, the Russian name means no more than ‘of the priest’ and designates a servant of a priest. Compare   Popoff  , see also   Pop   2,   Popovic  , and   Popovski   1.","Jewish (American): most likely a shortened form of   Popovski   2. Compare   Popoff  ."]},{"name":"Papke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Bernhard, Erwin, Hans, Otto, Willi.","North German (also <b>Päpke</b>): nickname from a diminutive of Low German <i>pape</i>, Dutch <i>paepe</i> ‘pope’. Compare   Pope  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":42,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Pope I was born in 1340, in England, United Kingdom, his father, Milo Pope, was 36 and his mother, Miss Arden, was 26. He married wife John Pope I. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1400, in Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England, at the age of 61."},"et":{"1340–about 1400":"1340–umbes 1400","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","1340–1400":"1340–1400","1345–Female":"1345–Surnud","1375–1460":"1375–1460","1305–Male":"1305–Surnud","1315–Female":"1315–Surnud","1305":"1305","1315":"1315","before 1335":"enne 1335","1335":"1335","1345":"1345","1400":"1400","1375":"1375","about 1400":"umbes 1400","1340":"1340","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","Europe":"Europe","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England":"Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"1340–about 1400":"1340–noin 1400","1335–Male":"1335–Kuollut","1340–1400":"1340–1400","1345–Female":"1345–Kuollut","1375–1460":"1375–1460","1305–Male":"1305–Kuollut","1315–Female":"1315–Kuollut","1305":"1305","1315":"1315","before 1335":"ennen vuotta 1335","1335":"1335","1345":"1345","1400":"1400","1375":"1375","about 1400":"noin 1400","1340":"1340","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","Europe":"Europe",